\clipboard {text:1.2}{\textcolor {blue}{ KMM methods set the source and target mappings $\fs : \Xs \rightarrow \X $ and $\ft : \Xt \rightarrow \X $ as a kernel-induced feature map $\phi $. The source and target domains $\Xs = \Xt $ are often assumed to be the same and the transformations are set as $\fs =\ft =\phi $. The shared domain $\X $ is typically a Hilbert space with a kernel $\kr : \Xs \times \Xt \rightarrow \R $ satisfying $\kr (\xs , \xt ) = \langle \phi (\xs ), \phi (\xt ) \rangle _{\X }$ with respect to the inner product $\langle \cdot , \cdot \rangle _{\X }$ in $\X $. However, we do not make these assumptions. We only assume that the distribution discrepancy between $\nus $ and $\nut $ is taken as in \eqref {eq:defn_D_MMD} and the empirical estimate is computed as in \eqref {eq:defn_hD_MMD}.  }}
\clipboard {text:1.3}{\textcolor {blue}{While \cref {assum_fx_bdd_moments} is stated as a general moment condition, it is naturally satisfied in the context of deep neural networks with bounded input domains. As formally shown later in our analysis of covering numbers (\cref {lem_cov_num_Fs_Ft}), standard neural networks map compact input domains (such as images with bounded pixel values, as defined in \cref {assum_Ax_Atheta}) to bounded feature representations. Since any bounded random variable satisfies the Bernstein moment growth condition, \cref {assum_fx_bdd_moments} holds by definition for the domain-adaptive neural networks studied in \cref {sec_samp_dan} and the datasets (MNIST, MNIST-M) used in \cref {sec:exp_results}.  }}
\clipboard {text:2.5}{\textcolor {blue}{Feature extractor networks in common architectures typically consist of several convolutional layers followed by fully connected layers \cite {SinghalWRK23}. In domain adaptation applications, it is standard practice to adopt convolutional layer weights from pretrained networks or to train them using source data \cite {TzengHSD17}. Our theoretical analysis focuses on the fully connected layers of the feature extractor, treating the input source and target samples $\xs , \xt \in \R ^{\dz }$ as the responses generated at the output of the convolutional network common between the two domains, as illustrated in \cref {fig_illus_ddan_network}. Notably, our experimental validation in \cref {sec:exp_results} employs complete architectures that include convolutional layers trained end-to-end; the consistency of the experimental results with the theoretical predictions suggests that our bounds remain applicable to practical architectures incorporating convolutional components.  }}
\clipboard {text:2.4a}{\textcolor {blue}{Dropout and batch normalization are applied after each layer. }}
\clipboard {text:2.4b}{\textcolor {blue}{Batch normalization and ReLU layers are included after each layer. }}
